<!-- COA-STP1 Sweden region-swap (reverse of R9): does COA-STP1's OWN unit data march
     if moved to the golden Sweden coordinates, or does it carry a problem beyond region?
     docs/UNIT_MOVEMENT_RESEARCH.md sec 4c (R9 forward swap: golden units -> Mojave, froze
     2/3). This file is the REVERSE direction: 2 of COA-STP1's OWN units -> Sweden coords.

     NOTE: this comment intentionally avoids writing two consecutive hyphen characters
     anywhere in its text (the CLI flag below is spelled without its leading double dash,
     and SIDC strings are described by their meaningful character rather than pasted
     verbatim) because two consecutive hyphens inside an XML comment make it malformed
     XML; a prior draft of this file used the literal double dash flag name and dash
     heavy SIDC strings in this comment and the app's XML deserializer silently failed on
     it (empty parse, 0 units). Keep this constraint if this comment is ever edited.

     Units kept (both carry their OWN explicit <Location> in the source file - confirmed
     via the offline parse-init check: no <Superior>/<CommandRelation>/<Subordinate>, so
     no superior coordinate cascade applies - grep data/COA-STP1_Initialization.xml):
       AD/7152  UUID 07894543-cfe5-765e-8c03-1e528d3f7350  EchelonCode PLT (platoon)
                SIDC echelon char (index 11) = 'D' -> UnitTranslator: ArmorPlatoon (AGG)
       3/7159   UUID 0a28b148-46b6-6058-af94-7738bacd3af7  EchelonCode COY (company)
                SIDC echelon char (index 11) = 'E' -> UnitTranslator: ArmorCompany (AGG)
     Both Side=00000000-0000-0002-0000-000000000000 (WASA) -> hostile relative to the
     first ForceSide (NATO Coalition, blue) -> HostilityCode "HO" (matches the source
     parse-init "Host=HO" observation) -> Force.Opposing in UnitTranslator.
     ForceSide scaffold: all 3 blocks kept (NATO Coalition FIRST - InitParser treats
     forceSides[0] as blue and reads ITS ForceSideRelation list to resolve hostility).
     CORRECTION (2026-07-15 live push): an earlier draft dropped the 3rd ForceSide
     ("Neutral") since neither kept unit references it directly - the port's own lenient
     InitParser accepted that (its hostility lookup only needs blue's own relation list),
     and the offline parse-init check passed - but the REAL C2SIM server rejected the
     push ("ERROR Error processing message", generic) because NATO Coalition's and WASA's
     OWN <ForceSideRelation><OtherSide> entries still reference Neutral's UUID
     (00000000-0000-0003-0000-000000000000), a dangling reference once its <ForceSide>
     object was removed. Re-added verbatim from COA-STP1_Initialization.xml. Lesson:
     the server does referential-integrity/schema validation our own parser does not -
     don't trim scaffold objects that are still REFERENCED even if not directly used.
     SystemName is "C2SIM" (copied from COA-STP1_Initialization.xml's own
     SystemEntityList/SystemName), so clientId=C2SIM is required for the parse-init check
     to report these units creatable (NOT "STP" - that is the golden init's clientId).

     COORDINATE TRANSPLANT ARITHMETIC (Mojave -> Sweden; inverse direction of R9's
     Sweden -> Mojave transform in docs/experiments/R9_region_swap_2026-07-13.txt):
     Native Mojave coordinates (data/COA-STP1_Initialization.xml, unchanged):
       AD/7152  lat=34.51930020274827   lon=-116.6936226485817
       3/7159   lat=34.33736748096155   lon=-116.51533760437191
     Native offset (3/7159 minus AD/7152): dLat=-0.18193272178672  dLon=+0.17828504420979
     Native great-circle separation (haversine): 26012.200 m

     R9's rule preserves ground distance via dLon_target = dLon_source * cos(lat_source)
     divided by cos(lat_target) (this is the SAME direction the rule always points:
     multiply by the source latitude's cosine, divide by the target latitude's cosine;
     R9's own worked example, Sweden(58.69) to Mojave(34.6), used cos(58.69)/cos(34.6)
     =0.6313 because there "source"=Sweden). Applying the identical rule with our
     source/target swapped (source=Mojave~34.52, target=Sweden anchor 58.71) gives
     scale = cos(34.51930020274827)/cos(58.71) = 1.586413, the RECIPROCAL of R9's 0.6313
     (1/0.6313=1.584, matching to the small difference in anchor latitude used).
     [Falsification check performed: applying cos(58.7)/cos(34.5)=0.630 (R9's numeric
     ratio taken verbatim rather than re-derived for the swapped direction) reproduces
     only 81.7% of the native separation, an 18% distance error that fails the "few
     percent" sanity gate below, so the reciprocal (1.586413) is the one used here.]

     Anchor: AD/7152 placed at (58.71, 16.45), inside the golden Sweden AO (telemetry
     observed golden unit footprint about 58.69 to 58.75 N, 16.32 to 16.52 E, R9
     evidence file). 3/7159 = anchor + (dLat unscaled, dLon * 1.586413):
       new lat = 58.71 + (-0.18193272178672)          = 58.52806727821328
       new lon = 16.45 + (0.17828504420979*1.586413)  = 16.732833735916422
     Sanity check (haversine, same formula both ways):
       native separation       = 26012.200 m
       transplanted separation = 26027.783 m
       ratio = 1.00060 (0.06% error), matching R9's own "9344 m maps to 9346 m" (0.02%)
       precedent to within a few percent.
     3/7159 lands about 26 km SE of the AD/7152 anchor (the real native separation is
     large; this is inherent to the two units' true relative positions in COA-STP1, not
     an artifact of the transform); both remain within the broader Sweden region the
     golden scenario occupies, just not inside the tight ~6x12 km golden cluster box.

     SECOND CORRECTION (2026-07-15, live push, found by bisection): with the Neutral
     ForceSide restored, the push STILL failed identically. Root cause was this very
     comment's POSITION: it originally sat in the XML PROLOG, before the MessageBody root
     element (standard-legal XML - xmllint confirmed well-formed, and the port's own
     lenient parser accepted it) - but the real C2SIM server's parser does not tolerate a
     large comment before the root element and silently fails the whole message ("ERROR
     Error processing message", no specific detail). Proven by bisection: stripping the
     prolog comment entirely made an otherwise-identical push succeed; reverting
     coordinates to the original Mojave values while KEEPING the prolog comment still
     failed, isolating comment POSITION (not coordinates, not ForceSides) as the cause.
     Fix: this comment now lives INSIDE the root element (right after the opening
     MessageBody tag), not before it. Lesson for future init/order files: keep
     documentation comments inside the root element, never in the prolog. -->
